GAO 's findings are particularly troubling because the FHA has about $ 300 billion in obligations outstanding and had previously been considered one of the most financially secure credit programs .
( Secondary guarantees of pools of FHA - and VA-backed loans by the agency known as Ginnie Mae currently exceed $ 330 billion .
Thus , subsidized loans tend to turn into giveaway programs , with increasing subsidy and default rates over time .
Given the structure of most credit programs , it is surprising that default rates are not even higher .
Guarantee rates are typically 100 % , giving lenders little reason to screen customers carefully .
But it would also encourage lenders to choose more creditworthy customers , and go a long way toward reducing defaults .
Until GAO 's recent audit , FHA books had not been subject to a complete external audit in 15 years .
Establishing these practices would permit earlier identification of emerging financial crises , provide better information for loan sales and budgeting decisions , and reduce fraud .
