Even if splits did affect stock prices , some academics argue that it would be futile for investors to try to take advantage of them .
`` Normally , the investor is n't able to benefit '' by buying a company 's stock immediately after news of a split , says Frank K. Reilly , a Notre Dame professor of finance and co-author of a 1981 study on splits .
`` The only thing that changes with a split is the brokerage commissions , and they often go up sharply .
